#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:236
msgid "Package class architecture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:240
msgid ""
"This section aims to provide a high-level knowledge of how the package class "
"architecture evolved in Spack, and provides some insights on the current "
"design."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:242
msgid ""
"Packages in Spack were originally designed to support only a single build "
"system. The overall class structure for a package looked like:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:249
msgid ""
"In this architecture the base class ``AutotoolsPackage`` was responsible for "
"both the metadata related to the ``autotools`` build system (e.g. "
"dependencies or variants common to all packages using it), and for encoding "
"the default installation procedure."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:251
msgid ""
"In reality, a non-negligible number of packages are either changing their "
"build system during the evolution of the project, or using different build "
"systems for different platforms. An architecture based on a single class "
"requires hacks or other workarounds to deal with these cases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:254
msgid ""
"To support a model more adherent to reality, Spack v0.19 changed its "
"internal design by extracting the attributes and methods related to building "
"a software into a separate hierarchy:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:260
msgid ""
"In this new format each ``package.py`` contains one ``*Package`` class that "
"gathers all the metadata, and one or more ``*Builder`` classes that encode "
"the installation procedure. A specific builder object is created just before "
"the software is built, so at a time where Spack knows which build system "
"needs to be used for the current installation, and receives a ``package`` "
"object during initialization."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:264
msgid "Compatibility with single-class format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:266
msgid ""
"Internally, Spack always uses builders to perform operations related to the "
"installation of a specific software. The builders are created in the ``spack."
"builder.create`` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:269
msgid ""
"def create(pkg: spack.package_base.PackageBase) -> \"Builder\":\n"
"    \"\"\"Given a package object with an associated concrete spec, return "
"the builder object that can\n"
"    install it.\"\"\"\n"
"    if id(pkg) not in _BUILDERS:\n"
"        _BUILDERS[id(pkg)] = _create(pkg)\n"
"    return _BUILDERS[id(pkg)]\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:272
msgid ""
"To achieve backward compatibility with the single-class format Spack creates "
"in this function a special \"adapter builder\", if no custom builder is "
"detected in the recipe:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:278
msgid ""
"Overall the role of the adapter is to route access to attributes of methods "
"first through the ``*Package`` hierarchy, and then back to the base class "
"builder. This is schematically shown in the diagram above, where the adapter "
"role is to \"emulate\" a method resolution order like the one represented by "
"the red arrows."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:285
msgid "Writing commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:287
msgid ""
"Adding a new command to Spack is easy. Simply add a ``<name>.py`` file to "
"``lib/spack/spack/cmd/``, where ``<name>`` is the name of the subcommand. At "
"a bare minimum, two functions are required in this file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:292
msgid "``setup_parser()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:294
msgid ""
"Unless your command does not accept any arguments, a ``setup_parser()`` "
"function is required to define what arguments and flags your command takes. "
"See the `Argparse documentation <https://docs.python.org/3/library/argparse."
"html>`_ for more details on how to add arguments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:297
msgid ""
"Some commands have a set of subcommands, like ``spack compiler find`` or "
"``spack module lmod refresh``. You can add subparsers to your parser to "
"handle this. Check out ``spack edit --command compiler`` for an example of "
"this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:301
msgid ""
"Many commands take the same arguments and flags. These arguments should be "
"defined in ``lib/spack/spack/cmd/common/arguments.py`` so that they do not "
"need to be redefined in multiple commands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:305
msgid "``<name>()``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:307
msgid ""
"In order to run your command, Spack searches for a function with the same "
"name as your command in ``<name>.py``. This is the main method for your "
"command and can call other helper methods to handle common tasks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:310
msgid ""
"Remember, before adding a new command, think to yourself whether or not this "
"new command is actually necessary. Sometimes, the functionality you desire "
"can be added to an existing command. Also, remember to add unit tests for "
"your command. If it is not used very frequently, changes to the rest of "
"Spack can cause your command to break without sufficient unit tests to "
"prevent this from happening."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:315
msgid ""
"Whenever you add/remove/rename a command or flags for an existing command, "
"make sure to update Spack's `Bash tab completion script <https://github.com/"
"spack/spack/blob/develop/share/spack/spack-completion.bash>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:319
msgid "Writing Hooks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:321
msgid ""
"A hook is a callback that makes it easy to design functions that run for "
"different events. We do this by defining hook types and then inserting them "
"at different places in the Spack codebase. Whenever a hook type triggers by "
"way of a function call, we find all the hooks of that type and run them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:325
msgid ""
"Spack defines hooks by way of a module in the ``lib/spack/spack/hooks`` "
"directory. This module has to be registered in ``lib/spack/spack/hooks/"
"__init__.py`` so that Spack is aware of it. This section will cover the "
"basic kind of hooks and how to write them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:330
msgid "Types of Hooks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:332
msgid ""
"The following hooks are currently implemented to make it easy for you, the "
"developer, to add hooks at different stages of a Spack install or similar. "
"If there is a hook that you would like and it is missing, you can propose to "
"add a new one."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:336
msgid "``pre_install(spec)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:338
msgid ""
"A ``pre_install`` hook is run within the install subprocess, directly before "
"the installation starts. It expects a single argument of a spec."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:343
msgid "``post_install(spec, explicit=None)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:345
msgid ""
"A ``post_install`` hook is run within the install subprocess, directly after "
"the installation finishes, but before the build stage is removed and the "
"spec is registered in the database. It expects two arguments: the spec and "
"an optional boolean indicating whether this spec is being installed "
"explicitly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:349
msgid "``pre_uninstall(spec)`` and ``post_uninstall(spec)``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:351
msgid ""
"These hooks are currently used for cleaning up module files after uninstall."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:355
msgid "Adding a New Hook Type"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:357
msgid ""
"Adding a new hook type is very simple! In ``lib/spack/spack/hooks/__init__."
"py``, you can simply create a new ``HookRunner`` that is named to match your "
"new hook. For example, let's say you want to add a new hook called "
"``post_log_write`` to trigger after anything is written to a logger. You "
"would add it as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:362
msgid ""
"# pre/post install and run by the install subprocess\n"
"pre_install = HookRunner(\"pre_install\")\n"
"post_install = HookRunner(\"post_install\")\n"
"\n"
"# hooks related to logging\n"
"post_log_write = HookRunner(\"post_log_write\")  # <- here is my new hook!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:372
msgid ""
"You then need to decide what arguments your hook would expect. Since this is "
"related to logging, let's say that you want a message and level. That means "
"that when you add a Python file to the ``lib/spack/spack/hooks`` folder with "
"one or more callbacks intended to be triggered by this hook, you might use "
"your new hook as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:376
msgid ""
"def post_log_write(message, level):\n"
"    \"\"\"Do something custom with the message and level every time we "
"write\n"
"    to the log\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    print(\"running post_log_write!\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:385
msgid ""
"To use the hook, we would call it as follows somewhere in the logic to do "
"logging. In this example, we use it outside of a logger that is already "
"defined:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:388
msgid ""
"import spack.hooks\n"
"\n"
"# We do something here to generate a logger and message\n"
"spack.hooks.post_log_write(message, logger.level)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:396
msgid ""
"This is not to say that this would be the best way to implement an "
"integration with the logger (you would probably want to write a custom "
"logger, or you could have the hook defined within the logger), but it serves "
"as an example of writing a hook."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:402
msgid "Unit testing"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:405
msgid "Developer environment"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:409
msgid ""
"This is an experimental feature. It is expected to change and you should not "
"use it in a production environment."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:413
msgid ""
"When installing a package, we currently have support to export environment "
"variables to specify adding debug flags to the build. By default, a package "
"installation will build without any debug flags. However, if you want to add "
"them, you can export:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:417
msgid ""
"export SPACK_ADD_DEBUG_FLAGS=true\n"
"spack install zlib"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:423
msgid ""
"If you want to add custom flags, you should export an additional variable:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:425
msgid ""
"export SPACK_ADD_DEBUG_FLAGS=true\n"
"export SPACK_DEBUG_FLAGS=\"-g\"\n"
"spack install zlib"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:431
msgid ""
"These environment variables will eventually be integrated into Spack so they "
"are set from the command line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:434
msgid "Developer commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:439
msgid "``spack doc``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:444
msgid "``spack style``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:446
msgid ""
"``spack style`` exists to help the developer check imports and style with "
"mypy, Flake8, isort, and (soon) Black. To run all style checks, simply do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:449
msgid "$ spack style"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:453
msgid "To run automatic fixes for isort, you can do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:455
msgid "$ spack style --fix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:459
msgid ""
"You do not need any of these Python packages installed on your system for "
"the checks to work! Spack will bootstrap install them from packages for your "
"use."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:463
msgid "``spack unit-test``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:465
msgid ""
"See the :ref:`contributor guide section <cmd-spack-unit-test>` on ``spack "
"unit-test``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:470
msgid "``spack python``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:472
msgid ""
"``spack python`` is a command that lets you import and debug things as if "
"you were in a Spack interactive shell. Without any arguments, it is similar "
"to a normal interactive Python shell, except you can import ``spack`` and "
"any other Spack modules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:475
msgid ""
"$ spack python\n"
">>> from spack.version import Version\n"
">>> a = Version(\"1.2.3\")\n"
">>> b = Version(\"1_2_3\")\n"
">>> a == b\n"
"True\n"
">>> c = Version(\"1.2.3b\")\n"
">>> c > a\n"
"True\n"
">>>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:488
msgid ""
"If you prefer using an IPython interpreter, given that IPython is installed, "
"you can specify the interpreter with ``-i``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:490
msgid ""
"$ spack python -i ipython\n"
"In [1]:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:496
msgid "With either interpreter you can run a single command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:498
msgid ""
"$ spack python -c 'from spack.concretize import concretize_one; "
"concretize_one(\"python\")'\n"
"...\n"
"\n"
"$ spack python -i ipython -c 'from spack.concretize import concretize_one; "
"concretize_one(\"python\")'\n"
"Out[1]: ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:506
msgid "or a file:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:508
msgid ""
"$ spack python ~/test_fetching.py\n"
"$ spack python -i ipython ~/test_fetching.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:513
msgid "just like you would with the normal Python command."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:519
msgid "``spack blame``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:521
msgid ""
"``spack blame`` is a way to quickly see contributors to packages or files in "
"Spack's source tree. For built-in packages, this shows contributors to the "
"package files in the separate ``spack/spack-packages`` repository. You "
"should provide a target package name or file name to the command. Here is an "
"example asking to see contributions for the package \"python\":"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:526
msgid ""
"$ spack blame python\n"
"LAST_COMMIT  LINES  %      AUTHOR            EMAIL\n"
"2 weeks ago  3      0.3    Mickey Mouse   <cheddar@gmouse.org>\n"
"a month ago  927    99.7   Minnie Mouse   <swiss@mouse.org>\n"
"\n"
"2 weeks ago  930    100.0"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:536
msgid ""
"By default, you will get a table view (shown above) sorted by date of "
"contribution, with the most recent contribution at the top. If you want to "
"sort instead by percentage of code contribution, then add ``-p``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:539
msgid "$ spack blame -p python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:544
msgid "And to see the Git blame view, add ``-g`` instead:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:547
msgid "$ spack blame -g python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:552
msgid "Finally, to get a JSON export of the data, add ``--json``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:554
msgid "$ spack blame --json python"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:562
msgid "``spack url``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:564
msgid ""
"A package containing a single URL can be used to download several different "
"versions of the package. If you have ever wondered how this works, all of "
"the magic is in :mod:`spack.url`. This module contains methods for "
"extracting the name and version of a package from its URL. The name is used "
"by ``spack create`` to guess the name of the package. By determining the "
"version from the URL, Spack can replace it with other versions to determine "
"where to download them from."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:570
msgid ""
"The regular expressions in ``parse_name_offset`` and "
"``parse_version_offset`` are used to extract the name and version, but they "
"are not perfect. In order to debug Spack's URL parsing support, the ``spack "
"url`` command can be used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:577
msgid "``spack url parse``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:579
msgid "If you need to debug a single URL, you can use the following command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:583
msgid ""
"You will notice that the name and version of this URL are correctly "
"detected, and you can even see which regular expressions it was matched to. "
"However, you will notice that when it substitutes the version number in, it "
"does not replace the ``2.2`` with ``9.9`` where we would expect ``9.9.9b`` "
"to live. This particular package may require a ``list_url`` or "
"``url_for_version`` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:587
msgid ""
"This command also accepts a ``--spider`` flag. If provided, Spack searches "
"for other versions of the package and prints the matching URLs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:594
msgid "``spack url list``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:596
msgid ""
"This command lists every URL in every package in Spack. If given the ``--"
"color`` and ``--extrapolation`` flags, it also colors the part of the string "
"that it detected to be the name and version. The ``--incorrect-name`` and "
"``--incorrect-version`` flags can be used to print URLs that were not being "
"parsed correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:604
msgid "``spack url summary``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:606
msgid ""
"This command attempts to parse every URL for every package in Spack and "
"prints a summary of how many of them are being correctly parsed. It also "
"prints a histogram showing which regular expressions are being matched and "
"how frequently:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:611
msgid ""
"This command is essential for anyone adding or changing the regular "
"expressions that parse names and versions. By running this command before "
"and after the change, you can make sure that your regular expression fixes "
"more packages than it breaks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:615
msgid "Profiling"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:617
msgid ""
"Spack has some limited built-in support for profiling, and can report "
"statistics using standard Python timing tools. To use this feature, supply "
"``--profile`` to Spack on the command line, before any subcommands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:623
msgid "``spack --profile``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:625
msgid "``spack --profile`` output looks like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:630
msgid ""
"The bottom of the output shows the most time-consuming functions, slowest on "
"top. The profiling support is from Python's built-in tool, `cProfile "
"<https://docs.python.org/3/library/profile.html#module-cProfile>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:636
msgid "Releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:638
msgid ""
"This section documents Spack's release process. It is intended for project "
"maintainers, as the tasks described here require maintainer privileges on "
"the Spack repository. For others, we hope this section at least provides "
"some insight into how the Spack project works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:645
msgid "Release branches"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:647
msgid ""
"There are currently two types of Spack releases: :ref:`minor releases <minor-"
"releases>` (``1.1.0``, ``1.2.0``, etc.) and :ref:`patch releases <patch-"
"releases>` (``1.1.1``, ``1.1.2``, ``1.1.3``, etc.). Here is a diagram of how "
"Spack release branches work:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:650
msgid ""
"o    branch: develop  (latest version, v1.2.0.dev0)\n"
"|\n"
"o\n"
"| o  branch: releases/v1.1, tag: v1.1.1\n"
"o |\n"
"| o  tag: v1.1.0\n"
"o |\n"
"| o\n"
"|/\n"
"o\n"
"|\n"
"o\n"
"| o  branch: releases/v1.0, tag: v1.0.2\n"
"o |\n"
"| o  tag: v1.0.1\n"
"o |\n"
"| o  tag: v1.0.0\n"
"o |\n"
"| o\n"
"|/\n"
"o"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:674
msgid ""
"The ``develop`` branch has the latest contributions, and nearly all pull "
"requests target ``develop``. The ``develop`` branch will report that its "
"version is that of the next **minor** release with a ``.dev0`` suffix."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:677
msgid ""
"Each Spack release series also has a corresponding branch, e.g., ``releases/"
"v1.1`` has ``v1.1.x`` versions of Spack, and ``releases/v1.0`` has ``v1.0."
"x`` versions. A minor release is the first tagged version on a release "
"branch. Patch releases are back-ported from develop onto release branches. "
"This is typically done by cherry-picking bugfix commits off of ``develop``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:682
msgid ""
"To avoid version churn for users of a release series, patch releases "
"**should not** make changes that would change the concretization of "
"packages. They should generally only contain fixes to the Spack core. "
"However, sometimes priorities are such that new functionality needs to be "
"added to a patch release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:686
msgid ""
"Both minor and patch releases are tagged. As a convenience, we also tag the "
"latest release as ``releases/latest``, so that users can easily check it out "
"to get the latest stable version. See :ref:`updating-latest-release` for "
"more details."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:690
msgid "PEP 440 compliance"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:693
msgid ""
"Spack releases up to ``v0.17`` were merged back into the ``develop`` branch "
"to ensure that release tags would appear among its ancestors. Since "
"``v0.18`` we opted to have a linear history of the ``develop`` branch, for "
"reasons explained `here <https://github.com/spack/spack/pull/25267>`_. At "
"the same time, we converted to using `PEP 440 <https://peps.python.org/"
"pep-0440/>`_ compliant versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:698
msgid "Scheduling work for releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:700
msgid ""
"We schedule work for **minor releases** through `milestones <https://github."
"com/spack/spack/milestones>`_ and `GitHub Projects <https://github.com/spack/"
"spack/projects>`_, while **patch releases** use `labels <https://github.com/"
"spack/spack/labels>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:702
msgid ""
"While there can be multiple milestones open at a given time, only one is "
"usually active. Its name corresponds to the next major/minor version, for "
"example ``v1.1.0``. Important issues and pull requests should be assigned to "
"this milestone by core developers, so that they are not forgotten at the "
"time of release. The milestone is closed when the release is made, and a new "
"milestone is created for the next major/minor release, if not already there."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:707
msgid ""
"Bug reports in GitHub issues are automatically labelled ``bug`` and "
"``triage``. Spack developers assign one of the labels ``impact-low``, "
"``impact-medium`` or ``impact-high``. This will make the issue appear in the "
"`Triaged bugs <https://github.com/orgs/spack/projects/6>`_ project board. "
"Important issues should be assigned to the next milestone as well, so they "
"appear at the top of the project board."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:712
msgid ""
"Spack's milestones are not firm commitments so we move work between releases "
"frequently. If we need to make a release and some tasks are not yet done, we "
"will simply move them to the next minor release milestone, rather than "
"delaying the release to complete them."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:716
msgid "Backporting bug fixes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:718
msgid ""
"When a bug is fixed in the ``develop`` branch, it is often necessary to "
"backport the fix to one (or more) of the ``releases/vX.Y`` branches. Only "
"the release manager is responsible for doing backports, but Spack "
"maintainers are responsible for labelling pull requests (and issues if no "
"bug fix is available yet) with ``vX.Y.Z`` labels. The labels should "
"correspond to the future patch versions that the bug fix should be "
"backported to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:722
msgid ""
"Backports are done publicly by the release manager using a pull request "
"named ``Backports vX.Y.Z``. This pull request is opened from the ``backports/"
"vX.Y.Z`` branch, targets the ``releases/vX.Y`` branch and contains a "
"(growing) list of cherry-picked commits from the ``develop`` branch. "
"Typically there are one or two backport pull requests open at any given time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:729
msgid "Making minor releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:731
msgid ""
"Assuming all required work from the milestone is completed, the steps to "
"make the minor release are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:733
msgid ""
"`Create a new milestone <https://github.com/spack/spack/milestones>`_ for "
"the next major/minor release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:735
msgid ""
"`Create a new label <https://github.com/spack/spack/labels>`_ for the next "
"patch release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:737
msgid "Move any optional tasks that are not done to the next milestone."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:739
msgid "Create a branch for the release, based on ``develop``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:741
msgid "$ git checkout -b releases/v1.1 develop"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:745
msgid ""
"For a version ``vX.Y.Z``, the branch's name should be ``releases/vX.Y``. "
"That is, you should create a ``releases/vX.Y`` branch if you are preparing "
"the ``X.Y.0`` release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:748
msgid ""
"Remove the ``dev0`` development release segment from the version tuple in "
"``lib/spack/spack/__init__.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:750
msgid ""
"The version number itself should already be correct and should not be "
"modified."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:752
msgid "Update ``CHANGELOG.md`` with major highlights in bullet form."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:754
msgid ""
"Use proper Markdown formatting, like `this example from v1.0.0 <https://"
"github.com/spack/spack/commit/b187f8758227abdfc9eb349a48f8b725aa27a162>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:756
msgid "Push the release branch to GitHub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:758
msgid "Make sure CI passes on the release branch, including:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:760 ../../../developer_guide.rst:824
msgid "Regular unit tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:761 ../../../developer_guide.rst:825
msgid "Build tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:762 ../../../developer_guide.rst:826
msgid "The E4S pipeline at `gitlab.spack.io <https://gitlab.spack.io>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:764
msgid ""
"If CI is not passing, submit pull requests to ``develop`` as normal and keep "
"rebasing the release branch on ``develop`` until CI passes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:766
msgid ""
"Make sure the entire documentation is up to date. If documentation is "
"outdated, submit pull requests to ``develop`` as normal and keep rebasing "
"the release branch on ``develop``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:769
msgid "Bump the minor version in the ``develop`` branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:771
msgid ""
"Create a pull request targeting the ``develop`` branch, bumping the minor "
"version in ``lib/spack/spack/__init__.py`` with a ``dev0`` release segment. "
"For instance, when you have just released ``v1.1.0``, set the version to "
"``(1, 2, 0, 'dev0')`` on ``develop``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:774 ../../../developer_guide.rst:836
msgid "Follow the steps in :ref:`publishing-releases`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:776 ../../../developer_guide.rst:838
msgid "Follow the steps in :ref:`updating-latest-release`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:778 ../../../developer_guide.rst:840
msgid "Follow the steps in :ref:`announcing-releases`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:784
msgid "Making patch releases"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:786
msgid ""
"To make the patch release process both efficient and transparent, we use a "
"*backports pull request* which contains cherry-picked commits from the "
"``develop`` branch. The majority of the work is to cherry-pick the bug "
"fixes, which ideally should be done as soon as they land on ``develop``; "
"this ensures cherry-picking happens in order and makes conflicts easier to "
"resolve since the changes are fresh in the mind of the developer."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:789
msgid ""
"The backports pull request is always titled ``Backports vX.Y.Z`` and is "
"labelled ``backports``. It is opened from a branch named ``backports/vX.Y."
"Z`` and targets the ``releases/vX.Y`` branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:792
msgid ""
"Whenever a pull request labelled ``vX.Y.Z`` is merged, cherry-pick the "
"associated squashed commit on ``develop`` to the ``backports/vX.Y.Z`` "
"branch. For pull requests that were rebased (or not squashed), cherry-pick "
"each associated commit individually. Never force-push to the ``backports/vX."
"Y.Z`` branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:798
msgid ""
"Sometimes you may **still** get merge conflicts even if you have cherry-"
"picked all the commits in order. This generally means there is some other "
"intervening pull request that the one you are trying to pick depends on. In "
"these cases, you will need to make a judgment call regarding those pull "
"requests. Consider the number of affected files and/or the resulting "
"differences."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:803
msgid "If the changes are small, you might just cherry-pick it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:805
msgid ""
"If the changes are large, then you may decide that this fix is not worth "
"including in a patch release, in which case you should remove the label from "
"the pull request. Remember that large, manual backports are seldom the right "
"choice for a patch release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:808
msgid ""
"When all commits are cherry-picked in the ``backports/vX.Y.Z`` branch, make "
"the patch release as follows:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:810
msgid ""
"`Create a new label <https://github.com/spack/spack/labels>`_ ``vX.Y.{Z+1}`` "
"for the next patch release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:812
msgid ""
"Replace the label ``vX.Y.Z`` with ``vX.Y.{Z+1}`` for all PRs and issues that "
"are not yet done."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:814
msgid ""
"Manually push a single commit with commit message ``Set version to vX.Y.Z`` "
"to the ``backports/vX.Y.Z`` branch, that both bumps the Spack version number "
"and updates the changelog:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:816
msgid "Bump the version in ``lib/spack/spack/__init__.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:817
msgid "Update ``CHANGELOG.md`` with a list of the changes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:819
msgid ""
"This is typically a summary of the commits you cherry-picked onto the "
"release branch. See `the changelog from v1.0.2 <https://github.com/spack/"
"spack/commit/734c5db2121b01c373eed6538e452f18887e9e44>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:822
msgid "Make sure CI passes on the **backports pull request**, including:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:828
msgid ""
"Merge the ``Backports vX.Y.Z`` PR with the **Rebase and merge** strategy. "
"This is needed to keep track in the release branch of all the commits that "
"were cherry-picked."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:831
msgid "Make sure CI passes on the last commit of the **release branch**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:833
msgid ""
"In the rare case you need to include additional commits in the patch release "
"after the backports PR is merged, it is best to delete the last commit ``Set "
"version to vX.Y.Z`` from the release branch with a single force-push, open a "
"new backports PR named ``Backports vX.Y.Z (2)``, and repeat the process. "
"Avoid repeated force-pushes to the release branch."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:842
msgid ""
"Submit a PR to update the ``CHANGELOG.md`` in the ``develop`` branch with "
"the addition of this patch release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:847
msgid "Publishing a release on GitHub"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:849
msgid "Create the release in GitHub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:851
msgid ""
"Go to `github.com/spack/spack/releases <https://github.com/spack/spack/"
"releases>`_ and click ``Draft a new release``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:853
msgid "Set ``Tag version`` to the name of the tag that will be created."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:855
msgid ""
"The name should start with ``v`` and contain *all three* parts of the "
"version (e.g., ``v1.1.0`` or ``v1.1.1``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:857
msgid ""
"Set ``Target`` to the ``releases/vX.Y`` branch (e.g., ``releases/v1.0``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:859
msgid ""
"Set ``Release title`` to ``vX.Y.Z`` to match the tag (e.g., ``v1.0.1``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:861
msgid ""
"Paste the latest release Markdown from your ``CHANGELOG.md`` file as the "
"text."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:863
msgid ""
"Save the draft so you can keep coming back to it as you prepare the release."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:865
msgid "When you are ready to finalize the release, click ``Publish release``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:867
msgid ""
"Immediately after publishing, go back to `github.com/spack/spack/releases "
"<https://github.com/spack/spack/releases>`_ and download the auto-generated "
"``.tar.gz`` file for the release. It is the ``Source code (tar.gz)`` link."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:870
msgid ""
"Click ``Edit`` on the release you just made and attach the downloaded "
"release tarball as a binary. This does two things:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:873
msgid "Makes sure that the hash of our releases does not change over time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:875
msgid ""
"GitHub sometimes annoyingly changes the way they generate tarballs that can "
"result in the hashes changing if you rely on the auto-generated tarball "
"links."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:877
msgid "Gets download counts on releases visible through the GitHub API."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:879
msgid ""
"GitHub tracks downloads of artifacts, but *not* the source links. See the "
"`releases page <https://api.github.com/repos/spack/spack/releases>`_ and "
"search for ``download_count`` to see this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:882
msgid ""
"Go to `readthedocs.org <https://readthedocs.org/projects/spack>`_ and "
"activate the release tag."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:884
msgid ""
"This builds the documentation and makes the released version selectable in "
"the versions menu."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:890
msgid "Updating `releases/latest`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:892
msgid ""
"If the new release is the **highest** Spack release yet, you should also tag "
"it as ``releases/latest``. For example, suppose the highest release is "
"currently ``v1.1.3``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:895
msgid ""
"If you are releasing ``v1.1.4`` or ``v1.2.0``, then you should tag it with "
"``releases/latest``, as these are higher than ``v1.1.3``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:897
msgid ""
"If you are making a new release of an **older** minor version of Spack, e."
"g., ``v1.0.5``, then you should not tag it as ``releases/latest`` (as there "
"are newer major/minor versions)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:899
msgid ""
"To do so, first fetch the latest tag created on GitHub, since you may not "
"have it locally:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:901
msgid "$ git fetch --force git@github.com:spack/spack tag vX.Y.Z"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:905
msgid ""
"Then tag ``vX.Y.Z`` as ``releases/latest`` and push the individual tag to "
"GitHub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:907
msgid ""
"$ git tag --force releases/latest vX.Y.Z\n"
"$ git push --force git@github.com:spack/spack releases/latest"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:912
msgid ""
"The ``--force`` argument to ``git tag`` makes Git overwrite the existing "
"``releases/latest`` tag with the new one. Do **not** use the ``--tags`` flag "
"when pushing, as this will push *all* local tags."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:919
msgid "Announcing a release"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:921
msgid ""
"We announce releases in all of the major Spack communication channels. "
"Publishing the release takes care of GitHub. The remaining channels are X, "
"Slack, and the mailing list. Here are the steps:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:926
msgid "Announce the release on X."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:928
msgid ""
"Compose the tweet on the ``@spackpm`` account per the ``spack-twitter`` "
"slack channel."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:930 ../../../developer_guide.rst:948
msgid "Be sure to include a link to the release's page on GitHub."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:932
msgid ""
"You can base the tweet on `this example <https://twitter.com/spackpm/"
"status/1231761858182307840>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:934
msgid "Announce the release on Slack."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:936
msgid ""
"Compose a message in the ``#announcements`` Slack channel (`spackpm.slack."
"com <https://spackpm.slack.com>`_)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:938
msgid ""
"Preface the message with ``@channel`` to notify even those people not "
"currently logged in."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:940
msgid "Be sure to include a link to the tweet above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:942
msgid ""
"The tweet will be shown inline so that you do not have to retype your "
"release announcement."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:944
msgid "Announce the release on the Spack mailing list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:946
msgid "Compose an email to the Spack mailing list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:950
msgid "It is also helpful to include some information directly in the email."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:952
msgid ""
"You can base your announcement on this `example email <https://groups.google."
"com/forum/#!topic/spack/WT4CT9i_X4s>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../developer_guide.rst:954
msgid ""
"Once you have completed the above steps, congratulations, you are done! You "
"have finished making the release!"
msgstr ""
